h3. Issue Summary
When installing Jira service using {{Service.bat}} shipped along with Jira 8.19 .zip archive for windows, there is an error witnessed stating below:
{code:java}
<jira_install_directory>\bin\tomcat8.exe.x64 "This file does not have an app associated with it for performing this action. Please install and app or, if one is already installed, create an association in the Default Apps Settings page."
{code}


h3. Steps to Reproduce
# *Required* 64-bit (Processor/Architecture) environment to reproduce the behavior
 # Download .zip archive for v8.19
 ** [https://www.atlassian.com/software/jira/downloads/binary/atlassian-jira-software-8.19.0.zip]
 # Extract the archive
 # Navigate to {{/bin}} directory and execute the {{service.bat install jira}}

h3. Expected Results
To have the service installed properly

h3. Actual Results
An error is witnessed:
{panel:title=Error Witnessed after executing Service.bat|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#000000|titleBGColor=#adcdff|bgColor=#d1e3ff}
"<jira_install_directory>\bin\tomcat8.exe.x64"' "This file does not have an app associated with it for performing this action. Please install and app or, if one is already installed, create an association in the Default Apps Settings page."
{panel}

Error is witnessed as .x64 is not recognized executable, there are restrictions in some environment to allow only certain executables like .exe to run

h3. Workaround
Remove below lines from {{service.bat}}:
{code:java}
IF "%PROCESSOR_ARCHITECTURE%"=="x86" goto notX64
set EXECUTABLE=%EXECUTABLE%.x64
{code}
Rename {{Tomcat8.exe.x64}} to {{Tomcat8.exe}} and {{service.bat install jira}}

Currently [our ZDU upgrade page|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/upgrading-jira-data-center-with-zero-downtime-938846953.html] makes no statement about upgrading or not the apps (plugins), however [our ZDU development page|https://developer.atlassian.com/server/jira/platform/zero-downtime-upgrades-for-jira-data-center-applications/] does mention we should avoid upgrading them.
{quote}
Currently Atlassian strongly discourages admins from updating plugins during ZDU.
{quote}

It would be best if we can add this statement to the official ZDU upgrade page as well to prevent problems.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1391].
  {panel}

*Original request description:*
 
As a JIRA administrator I am responsible for managing a large installation with multiple users and groups. Given the dynamic nature of my environment it is very difficult for me to create the correct user group name which can be used for many projects later on. I need to be able to rename the user groups, to reflect the changes my organisation undergoes.

Summary:
Updating Sprint Goal does not fire a SprintChanged event

Steps to reproduce:
1. Add a handler that listen for {{SprintEvent}} events;
2. Change the Sprint Goal;

Expected results:
A {{SprintEvent}} is fired;

Actual results:
No events are fired whatsoever;

Workaround:
Use {{com.atlassian.greenhopper.analytics.SprintUpdatedAnalyticsEvent}} instead of {{SprintEvent}}

h3. Problem Definition
If a field has a value larger than 32766 characters it won't be indexed, and its contents won't be searchable. This is likely due to a Lucene limitation, as described in JSWSERVER-20133.

h3. Suggested Solution
Implement a feature to allow indexing of fields having more than 32766 characters.

 
h3. Workarounds 
* Set the parameter *{{jira.text.field.character.limit}}* to *32766* in *Cog icon > System > Advanced settings* so all new values entered in fields should be properly indexed.
* Use the *text* operator in JQL to search for text in all fields. Existing JQL queries would need to be changed. For example:
{code:none|title=Old JQL query}
"Custom Field Name" ~ "String to be searched"
{code}
{code:none|title=New JQL query}
text ~ "String to be searched"
{code}
